  "prompt": "What integer solutions to x and y are there for 167x+113y=1?",
  "response": "To find integer solutions for the equation \\(167x + 113y = 1\\), we can use the Extended Euclidean Algorithm. This algorithm not only finds the greatest common divisor (gcd) of two integers but also provides a way to express this gcd as a linear combination of the integers.\n\nWe start by applying the Euclidean Algorithm to find the gcd of 167 and 113:\n\n1. Divide 167 by 113:\n   \\[\n   167 = 113 \\times 1 + 54\n   \\]\n2. Divide 113 by 54:\n   \\[\n   113 = 54 \\times 2 + 5\n   \\]\n3. Divide 54 by 5:\n   \\[\n   54 = 5 \\times 10 + 4\n   \\]\n4. Divide 5 by 4:\n   \\[\n   5 = 4 \\times 1 + 1\n   \\]\n5. Divide 4 by 1:\n   \\[\n   4 = 1 \\times 4 + 0\n   \\]\n\nSince the gcd is 1, we can express 1 as a linear combination of 167 and 113 using the steps of the Euclidean Algorithm:\n\n1. Starting from \\(1 = 5 - 4 \\times 1\\):\n   \\[\n   1 = 5 - (54 - 5 \\times 10) = 5 \\times 11 - 54\n   \\]\n2. Substitute \\(5 = 113 - 54 \\times 2\\):\n   \\[\n   1 = (113 - 54 \\times 2) \\times 11 - 54 = 113 \\times 11 - 54 \\times 22 - 54 = 113 \\times 11 - 54 \\times 23\n   \\]\n3. Substitute \\(54 = 167 - 113 \\times 1\\):\n   \\[\n   1 = 113 \\times 11 - (167 - 113) \\times 23 = 113 \\times 34 - 167 \\times 23\n   \\]\n\nNow, we have:\n\\[\n1 = 113 \\times 34 - 167 \\times 23\n\\]\n\nSo, one particular solution for the Diophantine equation \\(167x + 113y = 1\\) is:\n\\[ (x, y) = (-23, 34) \\]\n\nTo find all integer solutions, we use the general form of the solution for linear Diophantine equations:\n\\[ x = -23 + 113k \\]\n\\[ y = 34 - 167k \\]\n\nwhere \\( k \\) is any integer. Hence, the integer solutions to the equation \\(167x + 113y = 1\\) are:\n\n\\[ (x, y) = (-23 + 113k, 34 - 167k) \\]\n\nfor any integer \\( k \\).",
